  "local_port": 53214,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "A bag contains 4 balls. Two balls are drawn at random and are found to be white. What is the probability that all balls are white?",
  "response": "Let's approach this problem step-by-step using Bayesian probability:\n\n1. Let's define our events:\n   A: All 4 balls in the bag are white\n   B: Two balls drawn at random are white\n\n2. We want to find P(A|B), the probability that all balls are white given that two drawn balls are white.\n\n3. Using Bayes' theorem:\n   P(A|B) = P(B|A) * P(A) / P(B)\n\n4. Let's calculate each component:\n\n   P(B|A): Probability of drawing 2 white balls if all balls are white\n   This is 1 (certainty), because if all balls are white, any 2 drawn will be white.\n\n   P(A): Prior probability of all balls being white\n   Without any information, we can assume any color combination is equally likely.\n   There are 2^4 = 16 possible color combinations (each ball can be white or not).\n   Only 1 of these is all white.\n   So P(A) = 1/16\n\n   P(B): Probability of drawing 2 white balls\n   We need to consider all cases where this could happen:\n   - All 4 white: C(4,2) = 6 ways to choose 2 out of 4\n   - 3 white, 1 other: C(3,2) = 3 ways to choose 2 out of 3\n   - 2 white, 2 other: C(2,2) = 1 way to choose 2 out of 2\n   Total ways to draw 2 balls from 4: C(4,2) = 6\n   P(B) = (6 + 3 + 1) / 6 = 10/6 = 5/3\n\n5. Now we can calculate:\n   P(A|B) = (1 * 1/16) / (5/3) = 3/80\n\nTherefore, the probability that all balls are white, given that two drawn balls are white, is 3/80 or 0.0375.\n\nThis result makes intuitive sense: drawing two white balls increases the likelihood that all balls are white, but it's still relatively unlikely given the small sample size and the possibility of other color combinations.",
